<body>
    <div class="header-box">
        <h1>Mental Health Awareness</h1>
    </div>
    <div class="card-container">
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_1.jpg" alt="Anxiety">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Anxiety Disorders</h2>
                <p><strong>Prevalence:</strong> Globally, approximately 12% of individuals experience an anxiety disorder during their lifetime.</p>
                <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Persistent and excessive worry, restlessness, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, muscle tension, and sleep disturbances.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> A combination of genetic, environmental, psychological, and developmental factors.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), medications such as antidepressants and anti-anxiety drugs, and lifestyle modifications including stress management techniques and regular physical activity.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_3.avif" alt="Depression">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Depression</h2>
                <p><strong>Prevalence:</strong> Depression is the leading cause of disability worldwide, affecting more than 300 million people.</p>
                <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Persistent sadness, loss of interest or pleasure in activities, changes in appetite and sleep patterns, fatigue, feelings of worthlessness or guilt, difficulty concentrating, and thoughts of death or suicide.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> A complex interplay of genetic, biological, environmental, and psychological factors.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Psychotherapy (such as CBT and interpersonal therapy), antidepressant medications, and lifestyle interventions like regular exercise and social engagement.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_2.jpg" alt="Stress">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Stress</h2>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Stress contributes significantly to mental health issues globally. In the workplace, depression and anxiety, often linked to stress, result in the loss of approximately 12 billion working days annually.</p>
                <p><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Irritability, fatigue, headaches, difficulty concentrating, sleep disturbances, and changes in appetite.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Workplace pressures, financial difficulties, personal relationships, major life changes, and traumatic events.</p>
                <p><strong>Management:</strong> Stress-reduction techniques such as mindfulness meditation, deep breathing exercises, time management strategies, regular physical activity, and seeking social support.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_4.jpg">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Eating Disorders</h2>
                <p><strong>Prevalence:</strong> Eating disorders have been on the rise globally. The prevalence increased from 3.4% to 7.8% between 2000 and 2018.</p>
                <p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Anorexia Nervosa:</strong> Restricted food intake leading to low body weight, intense fear of gaining weight.</li>
                    <li><strong>Bulimia Nervosa:</strong> Episodes of binge eating followed by compensatory behaviors.</li>
                    <li><strong>Binge Eating Disorder:</strong> Recurrent episodes of eating large quantities without purging.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> A mix of genetic predisposition, psychological factors, societal pressures, and cultural influences.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Nutritional counseling, psychotherapy (like CBT), and medications when appropriate.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_5.png" alt="Personality Disorders">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Personality Disorders</h2>
                <p><strong>Prevalence:</strong> Approximately 7.8% of the global population is estimated to have a personality disorder.</p>
                <p><strong>Common Types:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD):</strong> Instability in relationships, self-image, and emotions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Narcissistic Personality Disorder (NPD):</strong> Grandiosity, need for admiration, lack of empathy.</li>
                    <li><strong>Antisocial Personality Disorder (ASPD):</strong> Disregard for others' rights, deceitfulness.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Combination of genetic factors, early childhood experiences, and environmental influences.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Psychotherapy, particularly dialectical behavior therapy (DBT) for BPD, and medications for specific symptoms.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
            <img src="/img/mental/18_6.jpg" alt="Eating Disorders">
            <div class="card-content">
                <h2>Psychotic Disorders</h2>
                <p><strong>Prevalence:</strong> Psychotic disorders affect around 3 in 100 people at some point in their lives, with schizophrenia affecting approximately 24 million people worldwide.</p>
                <p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Schizophrenia:</strong> Hallucinations, delusions, and disorganized thinking.</li>
                    <li><strong>Schizoaffective:</strong>  Schizophrenia symptoms combined with mood disorder symptoms.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> A family history of psychotic disorders increases the risk, Abnormal dopamine levels and brain structure changes.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Help control symptoms by balancing brain chemicals, Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) for coping strategies.       </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
